The paper focuses on deep convolutional neural networks (DCNNs) and their success in computer vision and machine learning, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also introduces a new class of DCNNs called $\Pi$-Nets, which are polynomial neural networks, indicating that it could also belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of $\Pi$-Nets in generative models, such as StyleGAN, which suggests that it could also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper demonstrates the effectiveness of $\Pi$-Nets in a variety of tasks, including images, graphs, and audio, indicating that it could also belong to the signal processing (cs.SI) sub-category.
